This paper is about the development of a flexible, actuated spine for a quadruped robot, which is a topic that falls under the field of robotics. Specifically, the paper focuses on the hardware design, simulation, and testing of the spine, which suggests that it belongs to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves control and balancing of the robot, which could also place it in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of simulations and testing of the prototype could also suggest that it belongs to the Mechanical Engineering (cs.ME) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of tensegrity structures, which could place it in the Robotics and Automation (cs.ROB) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of sensors and measurements, which could also place it in the Electromagnetics (cs.EM) sub-category.
